The code statements that lead to the bug are:
```java
HttpMethod httpMethod = HttpMethod.resolve(methodParamValue.toUpperCase(Locale.ENGLISH));
return exchange.mutate().request(builder -> builder.method(httpMethod)).build();
```
Reason:
The `HiddenHttpMethodFilter` did not check if the resolved `httpMethod` was among the allowed methods (PUT, DELETE, PATCH). This lack of restriction allowed unsupported HTTP methods to be processed, potentially leading to unexpected behavior when simulating HTTP methods from HTML forms.

The code statements that fix the bug are:
```java
private static final List<HttpMethod> ALLOWED_METHODS =
        Collections.unmodifiableList(Arrays.asList(HttpMethod.PUT, HttpMethod.DELETE, HttpMethod.PATCH));
if (ALLOWED_METHODS.contains(httpMethod)) {
    return exchange.mutate().request(builder -> builder.method(httpMethod)).build();
} else {
    return exchange;
}
```
Reason:
The addition of the `ALLOWED_METHODS` list and the conditional check ensures that only the specified HTTP methods (PUT, DELETE, PATCH) are processed. If an unsupported method is detected, the original exchange is returned without modification, thus preventing unexpected behavior.

